The ESP32 just does one thing: reads sensors every 2 seconds and POSTs a JSON to your laptop's IP on the local network.
Your backend ingests it, feeds it into the simulation engine instead of the random generator.

MPU6050 for movement detection — straightforward I2C, well-documented
ESP32 WiFi POST — tons of examples online, 50 lines of Arduino code
Powering it from a LiPo with a TP4056 charging module

One glove with ESP32 + MAX30102 + MPU6050 sends real heart rate + movement data for one worker
The other 4 workers in your dashboard stay on the simulation engine (synthetic data)
The real glove worker shows up distinctly on the dashboard — maybe labelled "LIVE SENSOR" — so the contrast is obvious in a demo
